(449, 86, '_ttfmake:1463596479478:columns:1:content', '<h2>First Vote NC: An exciting new chapter for Kids Voting NC.</h2><p>The NC General Assembly appropriated funds from 2001-2005 to begin affiliated Kids Voting programs in 25 counties. The affiliates were different in structure but their mission was the same: to engage young people in the democratic process by conducting simulation elections. The counties eventually included:</p><p>[MAP]</p><p>These affiliates have implemented various outreach efforts to engage our youth:</p><ul><li>The distribution of civics curriculum materials</li><li>Staffing of Kids Voting booths at polling places</li><li>Simulation elections in schools</li><li>Voting parades</li><li>Youth-oriented candidate debates</li><li>Candidate guides</li></ul><p>Tens of thousands of young people have voted in elections run by Kids Voting NC programs over the years.Â While many of the programs are no longer active, a few affiliates still thrive with paid staff and office space while other programs remain active with volunteer support.</p><p>Elections have evolved and Kids Voting NCÂ is evolving as well. In 2016, the Board of Directors voted to change the name of the organization from Kids Voting NC to First Vote NC.</p><blockquote><p>Not only has the name changed but the model is changing to reenergize efforts and target the demographics of prospective young voters.</p></blockquote><p>First Vote NC no longer uses an affiliate model but instead has cultivated partners throughout the state, which includes former affiliates. The program focus will shift from poll site based voting activities to offering a project-based and curriculum-oriented model to be used in high schools.</p><p>First Vote NC has begun an exciting new chapter in Kids Voting NCâs history. We look forward to creating an engaged and informed electorate.</p>'),
