(124, 1, '2016-06-27 08:50:57', '2016-06-27 12:50:57', '<blockquote>\n<p style="text-align: center;">An exciting new chapter for Kids Voting NC.</p>\n</blockquote>\nThe NC General Assembly appropriated funds from 2001-2005 to begin affiliated Kids Voting programs in 25 counties. The affiliates were different in structure but their mission was the same: to engage young people in the democratic process by conducting simulation elections.\n\n<img class="size-full wp-image-139 alignnone" src="http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/kidsvote-map.jpg" alt="kidsvote-map" width="2000" height="807" />\n\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-132" src="http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/star.png" alt="star" width="100" height="26" />\n\nThese affiliates have implemented various outreach efforts to engage our youth:\n<ul>\n 	<li>The distribution of civics curriculum materials</li>\n 	<li>Staffing of Kids Voting booths at polling places</li>\n 	<li>Simulation elections in schools</li>\n 	<li>Voting parades</li>\n 	<li>Youth-oriented candidate debates</li>\n 	<li>Candidate guides</li>\n</ul>\nTens of thousands of young people have voted in elections run by Kids Voting NC programs over the years.Â While many of the programs are no longer active, a few affiliates still thrive with paid staff and office space while other programs remain active with volunteer support.\n\nElections have evolved and Kids Voting NCÂ is evolving as well. In 2016, the Board of Directors voted to change the name of the organization from Kids Voting NC to First Vote NC.\n<blockquote>\n<p style="text-align: center;">Not only has the name changed but the model is changing to reenergize efforts and target the demographics of prospective young voters.</p>\n</blockquote>\nFirst Vote NC no longer uses an affiliate model but instead has cultivated partners throughout the state, which includes former affiliates. The program focus will shift from poll site based voting activities to offering a project-based and curriculum-oriented model to be used in high schools.\n\nFirst Vote NC has begun an exciting new chapter in Kids Voting NCâs history. We look forward to creating an engaged and informed electorate.\n\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-132" src="http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/star.png" alt="star" width="100" height="26" />\n<h2>Leadership</h2>\n<img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-146" src="http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/hunter.jpg" alt="hunter" width="272" height="180" />Hunter Buxton is the Executive Director of Kids Vote NC. She is a graduate of UNC-Chapel Hill where she majored in Political Science with a concentration in Vocal Performance. Hunter began her career at the UNC Center for Public Television working in corporate and community relations, hosting the show <em>High School Assembly</em>, and voicing the book-loving mascot Read-A-Roo. She then moved to New Jersey and became a Program Officer for the Bonner Foundation. After taking time off to raise her three children and volunteer in the community, she rejoined the workforce as a consultant, advising small nonprofits on marketing and fundraising. She joined Kids Voting NC in the fall of 2014. As a college student she remembers driving 2 Â½ hours home to vote and immediately getting back in her car and driving the 2 Â½ back to campus to take an exam. She explains that her family was serious about the privilege of living in a Democracy and she had not yet learned about absentee ballots!\n\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-132" src="http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/star.png" alt="star" width="100" height="26" />\n<h2>Board of Directors</h2>\n<div class="text-col-sm-2">\n<ul>\n 	<li>Nigel Alston</li>\n 	<li>Dianne Davidian</li>\n 	<li>Gretta Dula</li>\n 	<li>Tom Duyvault</li>\n 	<li>Rebecca Hall</li>\n 	<li>Becky Johnson, Vice Chair</li>\n 	<li>Marian Lowry, Secretary</li>\n 	<li>Carolina McCollum</li>\n 	<li>Matt McGuire</li>\n 	<li>Daintry OâBrien</li>\n 	<li>Donna Rewalt</li>\n 	<li>Leanne Winner, Chair</li>\n</ul>\n</div>', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '86-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-06-27 08:50:57', '2016-06-27 12:50:57', '', 86, 'http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/2016/06/86-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(125, 1, '2016-06-23 21:56:03', '2016-06-24 01:56:03', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">First Vote NC: An exciting new chapter for Kids Voting NC.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nThe NC General Assembly appropriated funds from 2001-2005 to begin affiliated Kids Voting programs in 25 counties. The affiliates were different in structure but their mission was the same: to engage young people in the democratic process by conducting simulation elections. The counties eventually included:\r\n\r\n[MAP]\r\n\r\nThese affiliates have implemented various outreach efforts to engage our youth:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>The distribution of civics curriculum materials</li>\r\n 	<li>Staffing of Kids Voting booths at polling places</li>\r\n 	<li>Simulation elections in schools</li>\r\n 	<li>Voting parades</li>\r\n 	<li>Youth-oriented candidate debates</li>\r\n 	<li>Candidate guides</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTens of thousands of young people have voted in elections run by Kids Voting NC programs over the years.Â While many of the programs are no longer active, a few affiliates still thrive with paid staff and office space while other programs remain active with volunteer support.\r\n\r\nElections have evolved and Kids Voting NCÂ is evolving as well. In 2016, the Board of Directors voted to change the name of the organization from Kids Voting NC to First Vote NC.\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Not only has the name changed but the model is changing to reenergize efforts and target the demographics of prospective young voters.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nFirst Vote NC no longer uses an affiliate model but instead has cultivated partners throughout the state, which includes former affiliates. The program focus will shift from poll site based voting activities to offering a project-based and curriculum-oriented model to be used in high schools.\r\n\r\nFirst Vote NC has begun an exciting new chapter in Kids Voting NCâs history. We look forward to creating an engaged and informed electorate.\r\n<h2>Leadership</h2>\r\nHunter Buxton is the Executive Director of Kids Vote NC.Â  She is a graduate of UNC-Chapel Hill where she majored in Political Science with a concentration in Vocal Performance.Â  Hunter began her career at the UNC Center for Public Television working in corporate and community relations, hosting the show <em>High School Assembly</em>, and voicing the book-loving mascot Read-A-Roo. She then moved to New Jersey and became a Program Officer for the Bonner Foundation. After taking time off to raise her three children and volunteer in the community, she rejoined the workforce as a consultant, advising small nonprofits on marketing and fundraising.Â Â  She joined Kids Voting NC in the fall of 2014.Â  As a college student she remembers driving 2 Â½ hours home to vote and immediately getting back in her car and driving the 2 Â½ back to campus to take an exam. She explains that her family was serious about the privilege of living in a Democracy and she had not yet learned about absentee ballots!\r\n<h2>Board of Directors</h2>\r\nNigel Alston\r\n\r\nDianne Davidian\r\n\r\nGretta Dula\r\n\r\nTom Duyvault\r\n\r\nRebecca Hall\r\n\r\nBecky Johnson, Vice Chair\r\n\r\nMarian Lowry, Secretary\r\n\r\nCarolina McCollum\r\n\r\nMatt McGuire\r\n\r\nDaintry OâBrien\r\n\r\nDonna Rewalt\r\n\r\nLeanne Winner, Chair', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '86-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-06-23 21:56:03', '2016-06-24 01:56:03', '', 86, 'http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/2016/06/86-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
