(129, 1, '2016-06-24 10:29:06', '2016-06-24 14:29:06', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">An exciting new chapter for Kids Voting NC.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nThe NC General Assembly appropriated funds from 2001-2005 to begin affiliated Kids Voting programs in 25 counties. The affiliates were different in structure but their mission was the same: to engage young people in the democratic process by conducting simulation elections. The counties eventually included:\r\n\r\n[MAP]\r\n\r\nThese affiliates have implemented various outreach efforts to engage our youth:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>The distribution of civics curriculum materials</li>\r\n 	<li>Staffing of Kids Voting booths at polling places</li>\r\n 	<li>Simulation elections in schools</li>\r\n 	<li>Voting parades</li>\r\n 	<li>Youth-oriented candidate debates</li>\r\n 	<li>Candidate guides</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTens of thousands of young people have voted in elections run by Kids Voting NC programs over the years.Â While many of the programs are no longer active, a few affiliates still thrive with paid staff and office space while other programs remain active with volunteer support.\r\n\r\nElections have evolved and Kids Voting NCÂ is evolving as well. In 2016, the Board of Directors voted to change the name of the organization from Kids Voting NC to First Vote NC.\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Not only has the name changed but the model is changing to reenergize efforts and target the demographics of prospective young voters.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nFirst Vote NC no longer uses an affiliate model but instead has cultivated partners throughout the state, which includes former affiliates. The program focus will shift from poll site based voting activities to offering a project-based and curriculum-oriented model to be used in high schools.\r\n\r\nFirst Vote NC has begun an exciting new chapter in Kids Voting NCâs history. We look forward to creating an engaged and informed electorate.\r\n<h2>Leadership</h2>\r\nHunter Buxton is the Executive Director of Kids Vote NC.Â  She is a graduate of UNC-Chapel Hill where she majored in Political Science with a concentration in Vocal Performance.Â  Hunter began her career at the UNC Center for Public Television working in corporate and community relations, hosting the show <em>High School Assembly</em>, and voicing the book-loving mascot Read-A-Roo. She then moved to New Jersey and became a Program Officer for the Bonner Foundation. After taking time off to raise her three children and volunteer in the community, she rejoined the workforce as a consultant, advising small nonprofits on marketing and fundraising.Â Â  She joined Kids Voting NC in the fall of 2014.Â  As a college student she remembers driving 2 Â½ hours home to vote and immediately getting back in her car and driving the 2 Â½ back to campus to take an exam. She explains that her family was serious about the privilege of living in a Democracy and she had not yet learned about absentee ballots!\r\n<h2>Board of Directors</h2>\r\nNigel Alston\r\n\r\nDianne Davidian\r\n\r\nGretta Dula\r\n\r\nTom Duyvault\r\n\r\nRebecca Hall\r\n\r\nBecky Johnson, Vice Chair\r\n\r\nMarian Lowry, Secretary\r\n\r\nCarolina McCollum\r\n\r\nMatt McGuire\r\n\r\nDaintry OâBrien\r\n\r\nDonna Rewalt\r\n\r\nLeanne Winner, Chair', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '86-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-06-24 10:29:06', '2016-06-24 14:29:06', '', 86, 'http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/2016/06/86-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(130, 1, '2016-06-24 10:37:51', '2016-06-24 14:37:51', 'A one-of-a-kind online mock election platform is being developed by <a href="https://www.ednc.org/">EdNC</a>Â and will be ready in time to vote in the 2016 election.Â We are working with the <a href="http://humanities.unc.edu/civics/">NC Civic Education Consortium</a> to develop a teacher action plan and integration into the curriculum.\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">First Vote NC offersÂ anÂ experienceÂ that will truly impact students with a lessonÂ they will carry forward for the rest of their lives.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<div class="row">\r\n<div class="col-sm-2"><img class="size-full wp-image-80" src="http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/1.png" alt="1" width="58" height="91" /></div>\r\n<div class="col-sm-10">\r\n\r\nHigh schools across North Carolina will be invited to sign up to participate in the 2016 simulation election. Students taking theÂ <em>American History : The Founding Principles, Civics and Economics</em> course will serve as their schoolâs Board of Elections. As part of the project based learning initiative, they will make decisions about every step of the process, devise voter turnout campaigns, determine issue-based questions to include on the ballot, and publicize election results to the school community and local media.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="row">\r\n<div class="col-sm-2"><img class="size-full wp-image-81" src="http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/2.png" alt="2" width="72" height="94" /></div>\r\n<div class="col-sm-10">\r\n\r\nThe entire study bodyÂ will vote in local, state, and national elections using an online ballot, designed to be as close to the real thing as possible.Â The voting experience will conclude with an online exit poll that includes demographic and civic engagement measurement questions. The simulation polls will close at the same time as the regular polls â 7:30 PM on November 8, 2016.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="row">\r\n<div class="col-sm-2"><img class="size-full wp-image-82" src="http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/3.png" alt="3" width="67" height="94" /></div>\r\n<div class="col-sm-10">\r\n\r\nWhen the students arrive at school the next day, they will have access to all of the election data.Â This data will serve as the springboard for analysis by students in the Civics and Economics course.Â <em>Why did more girls vote at our school? Why did more juniors vote than freshman? How does our school compare to the district, county, and state?</em>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', 'How It Works', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '73-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-06-24 10:37:51', '2016-06-24 14:37:51', '', 73, 'http://firstvotenc.wpengine.com/2016/06/73-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
